Hal (hfinney@shell.portal.com) wrote:
: olson@umbc.edu (Bryan G. Olson; CMSC (G)) writes:

: >Using DH as Paul suggested does not require per-session interaction,
: >and Paul's requirement that all users share a common base and modulus
: >is unnecessary.  Alice publishes a, n, a^x mod n and keeps x secret.
: >Bob can then choose some y and send Alice a^y mod n followed by a
: >message encrypted with a conventional algorithm using (a hash of ?)
: >a^(xy) mod n as the key.

: Can this be used safely as a minimal identification scheme?  Alice has
: published as above.  To prove it is she, she responds to Bob's a^y with
: a^(xy).  Bob can confirm this is (a^x)^y.  I have seen similar but more
: complicated schemes in the literature but I wonder if there are weaknesses
: with this one.

I am not aware of any result showing this would or would not assist
Bob in breaking the system.

The schemes you refer to in the literature are probably zero knowledge
proofs.  With a zero knowledge proof, you can be sure that the identity
proving process does not provide a shortcut to breaking the system.
Why take unnecessary chances ?

--Bryan

